17.   Error Resolution Procedures.
ALL QUESTIONS ABOUT TRANSACTIONS MADE WITH Checking Pay MUST BE DIRECTED TO SPIRE, AND NOT TO THE BANK OR OTHER FINANCIAL INSTITUTION WHERE YOU HAVE YOUR ACCOUNT. We are responsible for Checking Pay and for resolving any errors in transactions made using Checking Pay. Spire will not be providing you with regular or periodic statements regarding your transactions. You should be able to see the transactions conducted using your checking account on the statement provided by the financial institution holding your checking account. The financial institution holding your account will make periodic statements available to you. SAVE THE RECEIPTS YOU ARE GIVEN WHEN YOU USE Checking Pay, AND CHECK THEM AGAINST THE ACCOUNT STATEMENT YOU RECEIVE FROM THE FINANCIAL INSTITUTION HOLDING YOUR ACCOUNT, YOUR BANK OR OTHER FINANCIAL INSTITUTION. If you have any questions about one of these transactions, call us at: 888-823-2438 or write us at: CheckingPay@paywithspire.com. We must hear from you no later than 60 days after your financial institution sent you the FIRST statement on which the problem or error appeared.
(a) Tell us your name, email and phone number associated with your access.
(b) Describe the error or the transfer you are unsure about, and explain as clearly as you can why you believe it is an error or why you need more information.
(c) Tell us the dollar amount of the suspected error.
If you tell us orally, we may require that you send us your complaint or question in writing within 10 business days. We will determine whether an error occurred within 10 business days after we hear from you and will correct any error promptly if you have not been credited by your financial institution. If we need more time, however, we may take up to 45 days to investigate your complaint or question. If we decide to do this, we may credit your account within 10 business days for the amount you think is in error, so that you will have the use of the money during the time it takes us to complete our investigation. If we ask you to put your complaint or question in writing and we do not receive it within 10 business days, we may not credit your account. For errors involving new enrollments, point-of-sale, or foreign-initiated transactions, we may take up to 90 days to investigate your complaint or question. For new enrollments, we may take up to 20 business days to credit your account for the amount you think is in error. We will tell you the results within three business days after completing our investigation. If we decide that there was no error, we will send you a written explanation. You may ask for copies of the documents that we used in our investigation.
IF YOUR PHONE, PASSWORD, PASSCODE, PIN OR ANY OF YOUR CREDENTIALS USED FOR Checking Pay ARE LOST, STOLEN, OR COMPROMISED, OR YOU WISH TO SUSPEND OR CANCEL YOUR Checking Pay ACCESS, NOTIFY US AT ONCE by calling 888-823-2438.
If you make a claim seeking a refund or provisional credit from us, you warrant and represent that you have not made a claim for the same transaction or received a payment or refund from any other party including but not limited to your depositary financial institution or a merchant. If you have received a payment or refund from any other party and you also receive a payment or refund for the same transaction from us, you hereby authorize us to immediately reverse the payment or refund given to you by Spire.
17.1 Disclosure Regarding Use of Checking Pay:
Spire provides the Checking Pay for merchants. The Services allow merchants to debit your account at your bank. The enrollment and the Service is not offered by the financial institution (your “Bank”) that maintains the deposit account that you have linked to your Checking Pay. The terms, benefits, and protections associated with your Checking Pay access may vary from those that apply to a debit card issued by your Bank. For example, if you use your Checking Pay access to make a purchase that exceeds the balance in the deposit account that you linked to the Checking Pay access, that account may become overdrawn even if you chose not to allow overdrafts with respect to a debit card issued by your Bank, and you may incur associated overdraft fees. Similarly, the liability limits applicable to Checking Pay access may be different from those applicable to a debit card issued by your Bank. Please see Section 13 for an explanation of your liability when using Checking Pay.
